<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="672" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[828,1437,1261,1796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,938,1325,1348]" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Remarks.</emphasis>
According to KඅඎǤ (1829: 2), the 
<typeStatus box="[1298,1344,1325,1348]" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">type</typeStatus>
material was collected (translated): ‘in South 
<collectingCountry box="[1213,1281,1357,1380]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, in the vicinity of Montevideo, Cassapava [= Caçapava do Sul], Porto Allegre by [Friedrich] Sellow’; the locality data were interpreted by following authors only as South 
<collectingCountry box="[1363,1433,1453,1476]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. In the same work, Klug described another 18 species of Cassidinae, most of which are very common and widespread through the entire basin of the 
<collectingRegion box="[1229,1302,1549,1572]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Paraná</collectingRegion>
River. Their 
<typeStatus box="[828,874,1581,1604]" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">type</typeStatus>
specimens are morphologically similar to populations from 
<collectingRegion box="[883,1074,1613,1636]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
while populations from the estuary of the 
<collectingRegion box="[894,967,1645,1668]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Paraná</collectingRegion>
River (including Montevideo area) are morphologically more or less distinct. Therefore, I assume that the Cassidinae were most likely collected in Porto Alegre or Caçapava do Sul, both located in the Brazilian state of 
<collectingRegion box="[828,1030,1773,1796]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="5" pageNumber="672">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
